Introduction¶

The main motivation for this blog post is to explore how the economic qualities of countries affects how they perform in addressing environmental challenges. Most people would assume that environmental issues are highly coupled to the economy through wealth, production, and consumption, but the relationship is one that requires good data to truly understand. Some conclusions may be quite unintuitive, while others are obvious but require data to back them up so that informed and effective policies and action may be taken.

Previous Work¶

The inspiration to explore this question was inspired by this blog post which sought to investigate the correlation between economic freedom and environmental responsibility at a national level. In fact, a couple of the plots here have been recreated based on that blog post. However, that post is only a jumping-off point––this blog post will do a much more thorough analysis of the data.

Data Collection and Curation¶

Yale Environmental Performance Index¶

The first dataset is the Yale Environmental Performance Index.

According to the website, the EPI looks at 180 countries and ranks them on 32 indicators from issue categories that span environmental health to ecosystem vitality. It looks at a very broad range of factors that all contribute to overall environmental performance, which makes it a great bird's-eye view for comparing countries to one another.

Of course, a bird's eye view means that you lose important lower-resolution details. A big part of this tutorial will be exporing those intricacies, which will reveal that all types of countries deserve both blame and praise for their environmental performance.

Importantly, the EPI can provide best-practice policy guidance for countries to understand how to best improve their environmental performance, both absolutely and relative to other countries.

First, import the necessary libraries that will be used throughout this analysis.

Each indicator is calculated from one or more data sources that are referenced in the EPI technical appendix. The calculations for each indicator vary widely. In aggregate, the ratings give a wide overview of how well a country is performing environmentally, but it is important to look at the individual indicators specifically instead of the overall EPI to understand the ways in which countries are successful and not so successful at achieving environmental responsibility.

Here are some details on a couple of selected indicators to give an example of what they mean:

MSW: Solid Waste / Waste Management / Environmental Health - Controlled solid waste refers to the proportion of household and commercial waste generated in a country that is collected and treated in a manner that controls environmental risks. This metric counts waste as “controlled” if it is treated through recycling, composting, anaerobic digestion, incineration, or disposed of in a sanitary landfill.

CDA: CO2 intensity trend / Climate Change / Ecosystem Vitality - The CO2 growth rate, which makes up 55% of the Climate Change issue category, is calculated as the average annual rate of increase or decrease in raw carbon dioxide emissions over the years 2008–2017. It is then adjusted for economic trends to isolate change due to policy rather than economic fluctuation.

GIB: GHG emission intensity growth rate / Climate Change / Ecosystem Vitality - Our greenhouse gas (GHG) intensity growth rate indicator serves as a signal of countries’ progress in decoupling emissions from economic growth. We calculate an annual average growth rate in GHG emissions per unit of GDP over the years 2008–2017. This indicator highlights the need for action on climate change mitigation in countries at all income levels.

Data Management and Representation¶

Data Exploration¶

Environmental Performance by Economic Freedom Scatterplot¶

The first highest-level bit of exploration that should be done is comparing the overall environmental freedom score with overall environmental performance. Whatever correlation we get from this data will have compressed a lot of important information into only two numbers and should be interpreted with this understanding, but it's a great place to start.

The first step to do this is joining the two tables together. There are multiple types of joins that can be relevant depending on what you want to do with the joined tables. Broadly, a left or right outer join will match rows one table to the other and use null values where there is no matching row. An inner join, on the other hand, only uses the rows which match between the two tables.

Since null values will only hinder the analysis for these purposes, the best choice is an inner join.

In [232]:
epi_efi_2020 = epi_2020.join(efi_2020, how='inner')

Similar to source [1], create a scatterplot to visualize if there is any correlation between EPI and EFI. The matplotlib.pyplot library is excellent for simple plots, though the Seaborn library is also a favorite among data scientists [link] and can have some improved functionality.

To create a scatterplot in pyplot, first use the subplots() function which will allow you to create 1 or more "subplots" in a single "figure". The second element in the returned tuple is an Axes object (or an array of them if you specify to create more than 1 subplot). Each axis object is what is used to create each subplot in the larger figure.

Use the scatter function and simply provide a pandas Series for x values and corresponding Series for y values.

In [233]:

Out[233]:
<matplotlib.collections.PathCollection at 0x7fcde9b279d0>

The scatterplot shows a general positive correlation with some notable outliers.

This intuition can be verified by plotting a regression line through the dataset. The linear regression line is the line that minimizes the residuals. A residual is the distance between a true datapoint and its predicted value (the y value on the regression line). In other words, it is the line which, if used to predict the actual y value for a given x value, would be the least incorrect for all actual datapoints.

A linear regression line is technically a 1D polynomial function. If we think of it that way, the Numpy library has some useful functions for making that line.

First, Numpy has the polyfit function which will perform linear regression and return the constant and coefficient that will define the line (the b and m in mx + b). Next, the poly1d function can take in those coefficients and return a function that takes in an x value and returns the predicted y value.

This line function can be plotted for all the possible x values to create the regression line.

In [234]:
# drop any rows that have a NaN in the '2020 Score' column, otherwise will be errors
epi_efi_2020 = epi_efi_2020.dropna(subset=['2020 Score'])

# we will reuse this function later
# it takes a dataframe, name of column for x and y values, and an Axis object to plot on
def plot_reg_line(df, x, y, ax):
    # create function to output values for line given coefficients
    _pf = np.polyfit(df[x], df[y], 1)
    _line = np.poly1d(_pf)
    # plot the regression line
    ax.plot(df[x], _line(df[x]), color='r')
    
# use the above function on the joined tables
plot_reg_line(epi_efi_2020, '2020 Score', 'EPI.new', ax)
    
# must have this here so that plot shows again
fig
Out[234]:

The line verifies the intuition for a positive correlation––we can see it goes up.

Hypothesis Testing¶

However, the correlation may not be statistically significant. The way to determine if it is statistically significant is by calculating the p-values for its coefficients.

The p-value is a measure of how likely an outcome is assuming that a "null hypothesis" is true. In this case, the null hypothesis would be that there is no correlation between EFI and EPI.

We can use the statsmodels library to recalculate the ordinary least squares line (OLS). The object returned will have a method pvalues that will return a p-value for each coefficient. This OLS line will have the same coefficients as the line that we created using Numpy, but Numpy does not let us view the p value as easily, so the statsmodels library must be used for this added feature.

In [235]:
# a function we will reuse
# takes in a dataframe, x and y column names
def print_p_values(df, xcol, ycol):
    # x column values must be reshaped so that each sample is an array of features (of size 1 in this case)
    X = sm.add_constant(df[xcol].values.reshape(-1,1))
    y = df[ycol].values
    est = sm.OLS(y, X)
    # fit regression line to OLS object
    fitted = est.fit()
    # access the p values and print them
    print(f'constant p-value: {fitted.pvalues[0]}')
    print(f'coef p-value: {fitted.pvalues[1]}')
    
# another reusable function that will print out the 
# parameters, meaning the constant and coefficient of the
# fitted model
def print_params(df, xcol, ycol):
    X = sm.add_constant(df[xcol].values.reshape(-1,1))
    y = df[ycol].values
    est = sm.OLS(y, X)
    fitted = est.fit()
    print(f'constant: {fitted.params[0]}')
    print(f'coef: {fitted.params[1]}')

print_params(epi_efi_2020, '2020 Score', 'EPI.new')
print_p_values(epi_efi_2020, '2020 Score', 'EPI.new')

constant: -14.271539070528465
coef: 0.990246604299394
constant p-value: 0.011918340818167433
coef p-value: 1.554930802785755e-21

What does a p-value mean? It is th probability of seeing a result at If the p-value is below .05, that means there is < 5% chance of seeing a result at least that far away from the value that is assumed to be true, assuming the null hypothesis is true. 5% is unlikely, so we can "reject the null hypothesis" and conclude that the data favors the alternative hypothesis, in this case that there is a correlation.

There are two important things to note in this case.

First, we need to select an alpha value. This is a value between 0 and 1. It determines the level below which a p-value is determined to be statistically significant. A common value for alpha is .05.

Second, the p-value given is a two-sided p-value. For this statistical significance analysis, we could have both positive and negative correlations, and thus positive and negative coefficients. Assuming the null hypothesis is true that the coefficient should be zero, we wa

The 5% of the probability distribution that is significant is thus devided

More Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Correlation Matrix Heatmap¶

Both EPI and EFI are aggreggate scores, so it will be very informative to understand how the different indicators in each index correlate to the indicators in the other index. For example, does population (from EPI) correlate with air quality (from EFI)?

This right data structure to represent all these correlations is, of course, a matrix. One axis will be EPI factors and the other axis will be the EFI indicators. Each cell will contain the correlation between those two elements, which is the slope of the linear regression line if those two elements were graphed on a 2D plane. That correlation can be positive or negative, of course.

This data structure can be visualized in the form of a heat map where the more positive a correlation the "warmer" the cell's color and the more negative the correlation the "cooler" the cell's color.

In [236]:
# create a large figure to fit all of the labels
fix, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,15))

ax.set_title('Environmental Performance Index vs. Economic Freedom Index Heatmap')

# isolate the names of the current-year score columns (i.e. H20.new and not H20.rank.new, H20.change)
epi_score_col_names = [ name for name in epi_2020.columns if "new" in name and "rnk" not in name ]

# isolate the column names in efi which have a float score value (omitting string data like 'Region')
efi_score_col_names = efi_2020.select_dtypes('float64').columns

# select those isolated efi and epi score columns from the joined table
reduced = epi_efi_2020[list(efi_score_col_names) + epi_score_col_names]

# run correlation
full_correlation = reduced.corr()

# reduce to a matrix of just (epi column names x efi row names)
mat = full_correlation[epi_score_col_names].loc[efi_score_col_names]

# replace the epi column abbreviations with their full names by looking them up in the indicators table
mat.columns = [ indicators[indicators['Abbreviation'] == abbr[0:3]].iloc[0]['Variable'] for abbr in mat.columns]

# plot the heatmap and make zero correlation black by setting center=0
sns.heatmap(mat, center=0)
Out[236]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Environmental Performance Index vs. Economic Freedom Index Heatmap'}>

Note: it might be useful to open up that heatmap in a new tab, otherwise you will be scrolling back to it very often.

This heatmap is extremely informative in breaking down the big picture trend and looking at the individual correlations that will better tell the whole story of what economic qualities of a country affect environmental performance.

There is lots of blue and lots of orange on the map which provides the intuition that the story is more complicated than the simple conclusion of more economic freedom being better for the environment across the board.

It should be noted the "more is better"/"less is worse" intuitions might be confusing for a few of the indicators. For example, the highest score on "Government Spending" indicates that the Government is not spending any money. So if more government spending resulted in a higher score on some environmental indicator, that would be a negative correlation. Just something to keep in mind.

More Exploratory Data Analysis and Communication of Insights Attained¶

Interpreting the Heatmap¶

It will be informative to look at an example of high, no, and low correlations in depth.

High Positive Correlation Areas¶

In the top left there is a bright orange area. This area is where "Property Rights", "Judicial Effectiveness", and "Government Integrity" overlap with environmental health indicators such as "Air Quality", "Unsafe Drinking Water", and "Lead Exposure".

This is a first major insight into why more economic freedom is contributing to higher environmental performance.

A good intuition here could be that

  • higher government integrity helps positive government-run environmental health projects get completed
  • higher judicial effectiveness ensures that entities that are damaging public health are held accountable
  • property rights is harder, but possible better property rights ensures more accountability from individuals to improve public health

But maybe it is not quite that direct of a causation. For example, a hypothesis could be that "Property Rights", "Judicial Effectiveness", and "Government Integrity" simply correlate the most with "GDP per Capita". Because of this countries with those 3 EFI indicators are the same countries who just have a lot a money and thus can afford to spend more on environmental public health measures.

To investigate this I want to confirm that "Property Rights", "Judicial Effectiveness", and "Government Integrity" correlate with increased wealth, so I plot all three of them with GDP per capita.

In the last spot I plot the GDP per Capita by 2020 Score to see if there is an overall positive correlation between a higher freedom score and richer countries.

In [237]:

Visually, I can see that there is a positive correlation for all of these plots. Therefore "Property Rights", "Judicial Effectiveness", and "Government Integrity" could simply be great indicators of a country's wealth.

In fact, the EPI website concludes from their own analysis that results from good policies can be attributed to wealth, especially in terms of environmental health.

More Hypothesis Testing¶

It would be useful to see just how tightly correlated economic freedom is with GDP per capita.

In [238]:
print_p_values(epi_efi_2020, '2020 Score', 'GDP per Capita (PPP)')

constant p-value: 9.014677720561101e-14
coef p-value: 3.1605852782000747e-21

The coefficient p-value is extremely low, which means we can say with a lot of certainty that there is a strong correlation.

Is more economic freedom always better?¶

So, overall, being a wealthier country is correlated with a higher EPI score. This begs the question––do economically freer countries always do better in terms of Environmental Performance.

Looking at the "2020 Score" row in the heatmap, the first column with a much lower positive correlation (very dark orange) is the Biodiversity and Habitat issue category. Plot it like previous scatterplots:

Ecosystem Services¶

Looking at the heatmap again, the Ecosystem Services column shows no correlation (black) with the Economic Freedom Index Score. Plotting this correlation will give us a better intuition into why:

The regression line slopes slightly down, however the coefficient p-value tells us that this correlation is not statistically significant compared to no correlation.

This can be seen intuitively because countries with both high and low Economic Freedom Scores score highly on Ecosystem Services. Similarly countries with both high and low Economic Freedom Scores score poorly on Ecosystem Services.

Overall, most countries score pretty poorly regardless of Economic Freedom.

Greenhouse Gas Emissions¶

So to summarize so far,

  • Environmental Health has strong positive correlation with EFI
  • Biodiversity & Habitat has weak positive correlation with EFI
  • Ecosystem Services has no correlation with EFI

So what about a negative correlation? Where are economically freer/richer countries doing worse?

Again looking at the heatmap row for 2020 EFI Score, there is one bright blue square––Greenhouse Gas Emissions per Capita.

Machine Learning¶

The line in the second plot seems to not fit very well however. The data doesn't seem linear in nature just by looking at it.

Let's try a machine learning technique to see if we can better predict the GHG score based on GDP per capita compared to a purely linear model. Admittedly, this example is a bit contrived, but it is a good demonstration of the power on a non-linear model.

A K-Nearest-Neighbor regression model is a good choice to compare to ordinary-least-squares linear regression. Other possibilites could be a decision tree or a non-linear SVM. Since there is only one "feature" in this model, the simplicity of KNN makes it favorable. If there were many more features the decision tree model could be an interesting choice, for example.

In order to properly compare the KNN and linear regression line, first find the optimal n_neighbors hyperparameter for the KNN model. This is the most important hyperparameter––it determines how many points the model looks at to make a prediction.

First, set up the X and y values to use for training.

In [244]:
# copy for cleanliness
_df = epi_efi_2020.copy()

# Must be reshaped so that each sample is an array (of size 1 in this case)
X = _df['GDP per Capita (PPP)'].values.reshape(-1,1)
y = _df['GHP.new'].values

The sklearn library provides a GridSearchCV functionality that runs a grid search over all possible hyperparameters and finds the best one based on the best cross-validation error.

In [245]:
# specify hyperparams
dt_param_grid = { 'n_neighbors': range(1,100) }
# create the grid search and run fit
# cv of 10 means the grid search will use 10-Fold cross-validation
dt_search = model_selection.GridSearchCV(estimator = KNeighborsRegressor(), \
                                         param_grid=dt_param_grid, cv=10).fit(X,y)

View the best selected hyperparameters:

In [246]:
dt_search.best_params_
Out[246]:
{'n_neighbors': 19}

Now that we have an optimal n_neighbors value of 19, we can compare how good the KNN regression model is compared to regular linear regression.

sklearn has a cross_val_score functionality that will do n-fold cross-validation, which can be averaged to prived a more accurate estimate of model performance. This is compared to choosing only one cross-validation train/test split and using that cross-validation error to evaluate the model. If you only choose one cross-validation split, you may get a biased estimate for the cross-validaton error that would be balanced out with more splits.

Negative mean squared error is used below as the scoring method. It is made negative so that a higher value means the model performed better (maximization vs minimization).

In [247]:
print('Linear Regression Results: ')
print(model_selection.cross_val_score(LinearRegression(), X, y, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean())
print('KNN Results: ')
print(model_selection.cross_val_score(KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=19), X, y, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean())

Linear Regression Results: 
-377.8604435371111
KNN Results: 
-216.8037239693661

The results show that the KNN Regressor has a higher (because it is negative MSE) error, which means it is the better performing model. Therefore, this nonlinear model is the better choice compared to using linear regression.

To visually see why, plot the KNN line over the scatterplot:

In [264]:
# get the fitted model
fitted = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=19).fit(X,y)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

# X needs to be sorted so that the line will come out correctly
# it needs to be converted back into a Numpy array afterwards
# so that reshape will work
_X = np.array(sorted(X.squeeze()))

# predict the y value for each X value
_y = fitted.predict(_X.reshape(-1,1))

# labels
ax.set_xlabel('GDP per Capita (PPP)')
ax.set_ylabel('GHG Emissions Per Capita Score')
ax.set_title('GHG Emis. Per Cap. by GDP per Cap. with KNN Line')

# plot the line
ax.plot(_X, _y, color='r')
# re plot the real points
ax.scatter(X, y)
Out[264]:
<matplotlib.collections.PathCollection at 0x7fcde9634940>

The line is a smooth curve, which is pretty impressive considering the simple nature of how KNN predicts values!

The flattening curve means that most of the worsening GHG emissions happen when countries begin becoming wealthier. Wealthy countries can become even wealthier with less and less loss to their emissions score. This could signify that they are decoupling their economic growth from emissions.

Insights¶

So what do we come away with?

By going through the data science pipeline, there is now a much more complex story about how economic freedom relates to a country's environmental stewardship. Economically free countries are wealthier, and that wealth is correlated with high environmental health ratings (clean air, water, sanitation, etc). While this is something to celebrate, this is only one aspect to environmental progress.

Economic freedom and wealth does not correlate as strongly with protecting biodiversity and conservation, which could be troubling, since it takes wealth to be able to afford to care about biodiversity and conservation rather than simply trying to survive economically.

Even worse, economic freedom correlates negatively with GHG emissions. The more free and wealthy a country is economically, the worse it is when it comes to greenhouse gas emissions. It is hard to put a value judgement on whether environmental health, biodiversity, or greenhouse gas emissions are more dangerous. Certainly, environmental health is a more immediate issue. But the devastation that could be caused by massive biodiversity loss or a rapidly changing climate is hard to predict because it is hard to model the complex effects of such changes.

Therefore, the high-level correlation between economic freedom and environmental performance can be said to capture the more immediate, easier to measure aspects of environmental performance. However, wealth has very negative correlations with GHG emissions, the negative impact of which is not possible to accurate evaluate.

Caveats¶

A major caveat in this data is that it does not capture "transboundary" environmental impact. This means it only evaluates a country's performance internally and would not include, for example, the impacts of a country via imported products. Later in this blog post we attempt to gather data on and visualize this important omission.
